==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slubber
<hw>Slub"ber</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Slubbered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Slubbering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. Dan.
<ets>slubbre</ets>to swallow, to sup up, D. <ets>slobberen</ets> to lap,
to slabber. Cf. <er>Slabber</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To do lazily,
imperfectly, or coarsely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Slubber</qex> not business for my sake.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To daub; to stain; to cover carelessly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is no art that hath more . . . <qex>slubbered</qex> with
aphorisming pedantry than the art of policy.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slubber</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slubber
<hw>Slub"ber</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A slubbing machine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slubberdegullion</ent>⟦br⟧
